Supply-chain hygiene, software bills of materials, provenance, and attestations.

This is the newest layer in container security, and it moves the question beyond is this image signed to what is actually in it, and how was it built. The first piece is a software bill of materials, a machine-readable list of every package, version, and license inside an image. You generate one with a dedicated tool or with build-kit's built-in support during the build, and it is attached to the image as a separate artifact referenced from the manifest, so downstream consumers can scan the list directly without ever running the image.

The second piece is a provenance attestation, which records how the image was built, the dockerfile, the source commit it came from, the builder, and the build arguments. Build-kit can generate this for you. Together with the bill of materials, a consumer can answer, in a verifiable way, that this binary came from this dockerfile, this source commit, and this base image. That is a strong claim that simply was not possible to make a few years ago.

Tying it all together is a framework that defines build-maturity levels, from merely having provenance, to having it signed, to running builds on hardened isolated builders, up to two-party review and fully hermetic builds. Modern continuous-integration systems can issue the higher levels automatically, and the full chain runs from a git commit, to a continuous-integration build that emits provenance, to a signed image and signed bill of materials in the registry, to a cluster admission controller that verifies the signature, checks the bill of materials is clean, and confirms the provenance. That chain is what modern production container security looks like today, and this notebook is enough to know what each piece does and why it matters.
